		<p>
			These pages contain all of the information needed to get started on BUGswarm development.
			At <a href="http://buglabs.net">Bug</a>, we are always looking for ways to improve upon the way we
			support our users and document our products.  If you have any questions, comments, or concerns, 
			please feel free to <a href="#">Contact Us</a>.
		</p> 
 
 		<div class="page-header">
 			<h2>Getting Started</h2>
 		</div>
 		
      <p>
			BUGswarm makes use of two primary APIs for configuring and participating in Swarms:      
      </p> 		
 		
 		<div class="row">
 			
 			<div class="span8 columns">
				<h3><a href="rest_api.html">REST API</a></h3>
				<p>
					BUGswarm uses a REST (Representational State Transfer) API for configuring Swarms and their Resources.
					The API consists of several HTTP GET, POST, DELETE, and PUT requests through the use of curl.  The REST
					API is not a streaming API. For each method call, a connection is opened, HTTP requests are sent, HTTP 
					responses are returned,	and the connection is closed.  This API is used for creating and destroying Swarms 
					and Resources, adding and removing Resources from Swarms, and generating a User's API keys.
				</p> 		
 			</div>
 			
 			<div class="span8 columns">
				<h3><a href="streaming_api.html">Streaming API</a></h3>
				<p>
					The BUGswarm Streaming API is used by Users and Resources to participate in a configured Swarm.  The 
					Streaming API also uses HTTP requests, however, it does not follow REST guidelines. In the Streaming API,
					connections are opened and remain open while HTTP requests are sent in succession.  This API is used for
					producing and consuming information from a Swarm.				
				</p> 			
 			</div>
 							
		</div> 
	
	</div>   
    
